}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1-9.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This elaborate way of telling time by the position of the sun and other stars in the \softline
heavens, inopportune in hell, where the sight of the sky is denied the travelers, will be a frequent \softline
feature of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  The four main points of reference are here (and on other occasions), \softline
Jerusalem, site of the Crucifixion and thus the most significant point on earth; the Ganges, 90}{\plain \fs24 \super\f1 o}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to \softline
the east; the antipodes, 180}{\plain \fs24 \super\f1 o}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to the south; and C{\f2\u225\'e1}diz, in Spain, 270}{\plain \fs24 \super\f1 o}{\plain \fs24 \f1  around the circle of the \softline
meridian, a great circle arc over Jerusalem.  This makes a right angle in its intersection with the \softline
plane made by the equator, which extends into a similar great-circle arc known as the horizon.  \softline
Each of the four equidistant points covered by the meridian is six hours from the other.  Thus we \softline
are told that it was 6pm in Jerusalem, midnight over India, and dawn here at the antipodes.  The \softline
location of noon is left unexpressed, but we can understand that it is in fact over Cadiz, and may \softline
choose to understand that the omission forces us to supply this last indication and perhaps to \softline
consider that this is the place associated with Ulysses' departure on his 'mad flight' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XXVI.106-111), especially since the concluding verses of the last canto had so clearly reminded \softline
the reader of Ulysses' voyage (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.130-132 and Hollander, "}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: The \softline
New Song and the Old," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis [virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 [1990], pp. 32-33).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The phrase at vv. 4-6 is complicated, but eventually comprehensible.  In the northern \softline
hemisphere, when the nights grow longer than the day after the autumn solstice, the sun appears \softline
in Libra, as a result no longer a nighttime constellation, and thus the Scales 'fall from her [night's] \softline
hand.'  However, in the northern hemisphere it is now just after the spring solstice and the night is \softline
found in Libra, while the sun is in Aries.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 10-12.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The mood of the travelers, compared by many, perhaps beginning with Benvenuto \softline
da Imola (comm. to this passage), to pilgrims on their way to earn indulgence for their sins, is not \softline
particularly eager.  Rather, they seem to hesitate.  Vittorio Russo ("Il canto II del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Nuove letture dantesche}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , vol. III [Florence: Le Monnier, 1969]), p. 243, cites Hebrews 11:13-16, \softline
with its insistence on the nature of life as a pilgrimage, as relevant to this tercet.  That passage is \softline
contained in one of the most significant texts in the New Testament giving credence to the idea \softline
that those who were born before Christ were nonetheless responsible for and capable of believing \softline
in Christ to come (all of Heb. 11 insists on the faith found in the great figures of the Old \softline
Testament).  But our pilgrims seem more at home with 'Egypt' than they are eager for the New \softline
Jerusalem, as were the Hebrews themselves in the desert (see Exodus 14:11-12; 16:2-3; 17:3) \softline
because they lacked a full measure of zeal for their journey.  For a discussion of the hesitance that \softline
suffuses this canto see Gorni ({\u8220\'93}Costanza della memoria e censura dell{\u8217\'92}umano \softline
nell{\u8217\'92}Antipurgatorio,{\u8221\'94} }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1\lang1040 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1\lang1040  54 [1982], pp. 53-70).  As Poletto (comm. to this passage) \softline
was perhaps the first to note, the phrasing here reflects that of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XII.6, where, in a \softline
simile, Dante is unsure about the path he should pursue.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 13-18.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This is, perhaps surprisingly, the first simile of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (there was a brief \softline
comparison at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.119-120; another at verse 11, just above).  While the first canto (vv. 19-21) \softline
involved a special relationship to Venus, this canto turns instead to Mars, treated here, as was \softline
Venus there, as morning star.  In his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , where Dante associates the first seven heavens \softline
with the liberal arts, he says (II.xiii.20-24) that Mars may be compared to Music.  He concludes \softline
(24): 'Moreover, Music attracts to itself the human spirits, which are, as it were, principally 
vapors of the heart, so that they almost completely cease their activity; this happens likewise to \softline
the entire soul when it hears music, and the virtue of all of them, as it were, runs to the spirit of \softline
sense, which receives the sound' (tr. Lansing).  We shall see that these notions will come into play \softline
when Casella sings Dante's ode to the new pilgrims at the mountain's shore later in the canto.  In \softline
his remarks on these verses, Bernardino Daniello was perhaps the first commentator to bring that \softline
passage in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to bear on this text.  But the valence of the passage as it is reflected here puts \softline
the alluring red light of Mars (and, later, listening to music, which is what Mars signifies in the \softline
earlier text) into a negative correspondence with the alacrity and whiteness of the swiftly \softline
approaching angel.  Looking west toward Mars implies turning one's back on the sunrise to the \softline
east.  Porena's commentary (to vv. 13-15) observes that Dante, as a Tuscan, was acquainted with \softline
this view of the sea, one found on the western -- and not the eastern -- shore of the Italian \softline
peninsula.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The opening verse of the simile has caused considerable difficulty because the early texts \softline
offered probably unacceptable readings and later attempts have been divided into two solutions, \softline
roughly as follows: either 'sul presso del mattino' (at the nearing of dawn) or 'sorpreso dal mattino' \softline
(covered over by the dawn).  This last is Petrocchi's solution, and we have followed it, if at a \softline
distance, in our translation.  Gabriele Frasca ("Dante, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II, 13, 44, 109.  Note filologiche ed \softline
esegetiche," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Esperienze letterarie}{\plain \fs24 \f1  9, 2 [1984]), pp. 79-81, supports Petrocchi's reading.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19-30.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The gradual revelation of the approaching presence (more light, greater size, two \softline
elements of white that then resolve to three [two wings and the angel's 'body']) culminates in \softline
Virgil's recognition of the angelic nature of the steersman.  For a brief account of the nature of \softline
and doctrinal problems inherent in Dante's angelology see Alison Cornish ("Angels," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Dante \softline
Encyclopedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Richard Lansing [New York: Garland, 2000], pp. 37-45).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The term }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 galeotto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (helmsman, steersman) has been used for Phlegyas, who carried Dante \softline
and Virgil across Styx in his skiff (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VIII.17 -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 galeoto}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).  It had previously been used by \softline
Francesca (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . V.137), as a proper noun, to cast blame upon the character Gallehault in the \softline
Arthurian romance that led, according to her, to her undoing.  The present }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 galeotto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is surely to be \softline
understood as a better-intentioned guide.  Dante has been cleansed by Virgil to be in the purified \softline
condition fitting for his presence before exactly such a being, 'il primo ministro... di paradiso' \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.98-99).  Hell had its guardian demons; purgatory has guardian angels.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 31-36.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's two balanced exclamations insist on the supernatural abilities of the angel.  \softline
The first has the effect of reminding us of Ulysses.  Where Ulysses made wings of oars (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XXVI.135), this traveler over the same seas before the mount of purgatory requires neither oar \softline
nor sail.  The word for 'oar' was last heard in Ulysses' speech (as was the phrase 'suol marino' \softline
[ocean floor] of verse 15 at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVI.129).  The word for poop deck, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 poppa}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , introduced to the \softline
poem to describe Ulysses' position as captain of his ship (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVI.124, repeated at XXVI.140) \softline
now recurs to set this celestial steersman against his less worthy counterpart (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.43).  For \softline
this argument see Hollander ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: The New Song and the Old," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis \softline
[virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 [1990], pp. 34-35).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The second tercet, describing the heaven-directed wings of the angel, may remind us of \softline
Satan's (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXIV.46-52) huge wings, if only by antithesis.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 38.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Lombardi, discussing this verse, pointed out that the 'uccel divino' (heavenly bird) 
stands in opposition to the demon Farfarello, a 'malvagio uccello' (filthy bird -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXII.96).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 39.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This is the first time in the poem that Dante is 'blinded by the light.'  Such scenes will \softline
recur for the rest of the two final }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantiche}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 42.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This detail almost necessarily reminds us of the contrary depiction of Charon's skiff in \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.413-414), sinking into the water of the swamp beneath Aeneas's weight, as Daniello \softline
(comm. to vv. 40-42) was perhaps the first to note explicitly.  See also }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VIII.25-27, when \softline
Dante's weight makes Phlegyas's skiff sink in the muddy water of the Styx.  And see the note to \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.136.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 44.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   A much-debated text.  The vast majority of codices and of commentators prefers the \softline
variant not chosen by Petrocchi: 'tal che parea beato per iscripto' (in such manner as to seem \softline
blessed by inscription).  Petrocchi chooses the variant 'tal che faria beato pur descripto' (in such a \softline
way as to render blessed anyone who reads or hears him described).  While we strongly side with \softline
the majority view, we have followed Petrocchi here as always.  Were we to depart from him, our \softline
translation would run as follows: 'whose look made him seem inscribed in blessedness.'  See this \softline
writer's earlier opinion ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: The New Song and the Old," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis [virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
6 [1990], p. 42): 'My own view is that the verse should be read in the spirit of Landino's gloss, \softline
which holds that he seemed 'inscribed, that is, confirmed in bliss,' in the sense (also tentatively lent \softline
support by Portirelli [comm. to vv. 44-45]) that he is written in the Book of Life' (see Apoc. \softline
20:12 and discussion in Hollander ["Dante's 'Book of the Dead': A Note on }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIX, 57," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  54 (1982), pp. 31-51].  For the only other use in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of the past \softline
participle of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 scrivere}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as a verbal noun see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XIX.54 -- and see the similar usage in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
I.viii.5.  In both these instances the verbal noun refers to a written document, as I believe it does \softline
here.'  Portirelli (1804) says that the angel 'seemed blessed by eternal and irrevocable decree.'  \softline
Most of the others -- the vast majority of commentators -- who read the line as 'parea beato per \softline
iscripto' interpret it to mean that the angel looks as though he were written on.  Landino, \softline
Portirelli, and Hollander believe that he seems blessed because he is inscribed elsewhere, an at \softline
least potentially more convincing reading.  Frasca ("Dante, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II, 13, 44, 109.  Note filologiche \softline
ed esegetiche," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Esperienze letterarie}{\plain \fs24 \f1  9, 2 [1984]), pp. 81-83, reopens the question of the reading \softline
of this line, but does not come to a firm conclusion about a preferable variant.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 45.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's 'more than a hundred' is a poet's allowable indefinite number, but one based \softline
on a very good number indeed, one hundred, number of God (1 + 0 + 0 = 1) and of the number of \softline
cantos in this poem.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 46-48.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The arriving pilgrims, seated in the ship that carries them to purgation and \softline
eventual salvation, sing the Psalm of the Exodus, 114-115 in the modern Bible, 113 in the \softline
Vulgate.  The text states clearly that they sing all of it in their shared exhilaration.  For the \softline
informing pattern of the Exodus in this canto (and in the poem as a whole) see, among others, \softline
Singleton ("'In exitu Israel de Aegypto,'" }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Annual Report of the Dante Society}{\plain \fs24 \f1  78 [1960], pp. 1-24); Tucker ("'In exitu Isr{\f2\u228\'e4}el de Aegypto': the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Divine Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in the Light of the Easter Liturgy," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The American Benedictine Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  11 [1960], pp. 43-61).  Freccero (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante: The Poetics of \softline
Conversion}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Rachel Jacoff [Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1986]), pp. 14-15, 55-69; 
Armour ("The Theme of Exodus in the First Two Cantos of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Soundings}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , \softline
ed. David Nolan [Dublin: Irish Academic Press, 1981], pp. 59-99); and Pasquini ("Dante and the \softline
'Prefaces of Truth': from 'Figure' to 'Completion,'" }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Italian Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  54 [1999], pp. 18-25).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For the pertinence of typical medieval rubrics to the Psalm, which divide it into three parts \softline
(the miracle of the Exodus, the Hebrews' backsliding worship of the Golden Calf, reaffirmation of \softline
God's continuing support), a division that is seen as paralleling the three scenes of the canto \softline
(completion of the 'exodus' of the arriving souls, Casella's song as 'idolatrous,' Cato's insistence on \softline
the pilgrims' devotion to God) see Hollander ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: The New Song and the Old," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis [virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 [1990], p. 36).  Each of these moments is assigned, as it were, a \softline
single simile that reflects its central action, the arrival of the ship (vv. 13-18), Dante's unique \softline
status as still living in the flesh (vv. 70-74), Cato's rebuke (vv. 124-132).  \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Since the words of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 incipit}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of this Psalm offer the basis for the analysis of the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as conforming to the analytical practice of allegory as practised by theologians to \softline
interpret the Bible offered in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Epistle to Cangrande}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , it is not surprising that those who believe \softline
that Dante is in fact the author of this document make much of its precepts in discussing this \softline
tercet.  It should be kept in mind that the citation of the Psalm here, ca. 1310, predates the \softline
composition of the epistle (ca. 1317-21).  Thus the epistle, if it is authentic (as this writer believes: \softline
see Hollander, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's Epistle to Cangrande}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Ann Arbor: University of Michigan Press, 1993] \softline
with bibliography of the debate to that date), does not describe proleptically the procedures of the \softline
poem, but reflects them.  The two most recent editors of the epistle, Thomas Ricklin (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Das \softline
Schreiben an Cangrande della Scala}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Hamburg: Meiner, 1993]) and Enzo Cecchini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Epistola a \softline
Cangrande}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Giunti, 1995]), both argue strongly for its authenticity.  For two attempts \softline
to counter the growing consensus that the epistle is, after all, Dante's own, see Brugnoli ("Ancora \softline
sull'}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Epistola a Cangrande}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Critica del testo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  1 [1998], pp. 985-1008) and Inglese ("Epistola a \softline
Cangrande: questione aperta," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Critica del testo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  2 [1999], pp. 951-74).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For this moment in which, according to a recent discussant, Dante decisively confronts \softline
and rejects the 'hard' poetics of his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 rime petrose}{\plain \fs24 \f1  for the 'liquid' poetry of salvation see Gianni \softline
Vinciguerra ("Petra / Aqua: della funzionalit{\f3 \'42} di alcuni salmi nella }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Critica del testo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  3 \softline
[1999], esp. pp. 896-909).  For the program of.Psalms and hymns utilized by Dante in the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  see Antonio Mastrobuono (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1\lang1040 Essays}{\plain \fs24 \f1  }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1\lang1040 on Dante's Philosophy of History}{\plain \fs24 \f1\lang1040  [Florence: \softline
Olschki, 1979], pp. 181-89); Louis La Favia ("' ...ch{\f2\u233\'e9} quivi per canti,' [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XII, 113]: Dante's \softline
Programmatic Use of Psalms and Hymns in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatory}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Iconography}{\plain \fs24 \f1  9 [1984-86], \softline
pp. 53-65); and Erminia Ardissono ("I Canti liturgici nel }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  dantesco," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  108 \softline
[1990], pp. 39-65).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 49-51.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Like the heavenly messenger at the walls of Dis (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.100-103), this angel, after \softline
blessing his flock, also moves away from those he has helped as quickly as possible, but on this \softline
occasion not from disgust at the place in which he finds himself, but to return to Ostia for more \softline
saved souls.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The souls fling themselves upon the shore (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 si gittar}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) just as the damned fling themselves \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 gittansi}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) upon Charon's boat (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.116), but with key elements in the scenes significantly \softline
reversed, though both groups are spurred by their desire for justice.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 52-54.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The second scene of the canto begins with the mutual pleasure and confusion of \softline
the two groups that play the major roles in it, the crowd of pilgrims and the two travelers, both 
less (in Virgil's case) and more than saved souls, since Dante is destined to return and will then be \softline
a uniquely experienced penitent.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 55-57.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   As Bosco/Reggio point out in their commentary to these lines, all the images in \softline
them are derived from hunting.  The sun (Apollo as archer), now risen above the horizon, shoots \softline
its rays (arrows) everywhere, striking the constellation Capricorn, 90}{\plain \fs24 \super\f1 o}{\plain \fs24 \f1  from Aries.  Consequently, \softline
Capricorn moves several degrees down the sky from its highest point, where it was at dawn.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 60.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For the resemblances of the mount of purgatory to Mt. Sinai see Carol Kaske \softline
("Mount Sinai and Dante's Mount Purgatory," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  89 [1971], pp. 1-18.).  For her the \softline
mountain is not only its former self, site of the divine gift of Ten Commandments to Moses, but a \softline
place of Christian pilgrimage under the New Law.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
