{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 63.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's reply to the saved souls identifies himself and Dante as being 'pilgrims,' in the \softline
generic sense that they are travelers in a foreign land.  In a more limited and Christian sense, only \softline
Dante and the new arrivals are truly on a pilgrimage.  This is the first of nine uses of the noun or \softline
adjective }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 peregrino}{\plain \fs24 \f1  that are distributed through the final two }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantiche}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  For the view that the \softline
controlling idea of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is that of a pilgrimage see, among others, John Demaray (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante \softline
and the Book of the Cosmos}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Philadelphia: American Philosophical Society, 1987], pp. 1-60); \softline
Bruno Basile ("Dante e l'idea di }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 peregrinatio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Il tempo e le forme: studi letterari da Dante \softline
a Gadda}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Modena: Mucchi, 1990 (1986)], pp. 9-36); Julia Holloway (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Pilgrim and the Book}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[New York: Peter Lang, 1992], esp. pp. 57-84); and Picone ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VIII: il viaggio contrastato," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 L'Alighieri}{\plain \fs24 \f1  9 [1997], pp. 35-50).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 65.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's recollection of the difficult journey up through hell is made to reflect the poet's \softline
own formulation in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.5 exactly: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 aspra e forte }{\plain \fs24 \f1 (dense and harsh), the adjectives there \softline
referring to the 'dark wood' of the world in which Dante found himself at the outset.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 66.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   These are Virgil's last words in the canto.  In fact he nearly disappears from the scene \softline
once Dante and Casella take over center stage.  He will be mentioned as forming part of the group \softline
of those who are rapt by Casella's song (verse 115) and as departing in haste with Dante in the \softline
canto's final verse (133).  In both cases he is behaving less like a guide than like a lost soul.  In a \softline
sense, this is the protagonist's first solo flight in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , a moment in which he is potentially \softline
in command of the situation.  His success is hardly dazzling.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 69.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Satan, with his three heads, had seemed a }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 maraviglia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to the protagonist in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
XXXIV.37.  In the last canto it was the miraculous 'resurrection' of the Christlike humble plant \softline
(verse 134) that had seemed a 'wonder' to him.  Now it is }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 he}{\plain \fs24 \f1  who causes wonder in the onlookers, \softline
since he is present in the flesh.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 70-74.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This second simile of the canto compares Dante's living visage to the olive branch \softline
carried by a messenger of peace.  In other words, his very presence in this precinct is an additional \softline
assurance to the new souls that God's justice and promise of a kingdom of peace as the final haven \softline
for a Christian life was truly offered and truly kept.  They have arrived, even if the way before \softline
them is uncertain and difficult, since they still have to perform their ritual cleansing of even the 
memory of sin.  While the earliest commentators do not cite a Virgilian source for the simile, \softline
beginning with Daniello (comm. to vv. 70-71), who was followed by Lombardi (comm. to vv. 70-71), Portirelli (comm. to vv. 65-70), Tommaseo (comm. to vv. 70-72), and Scartazzini (comm. to \softline
verse 70), later ones point to two possible Virgilian sources: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VIII.115-116 and XI.100-101.  Andreoli (comm. to verse 70) cites only the first of these.  In the second, messengers from \softline
the camp of Turnus, holding up olive branches, seek permission of Aeneas to gather the bodies of \softline
the dead for burial; in the first it is Aeneas himself, standing upon the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 puppis}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (quarterdeck) of his \softline
ship, who holds forth the branch of peace to Pallas, son of Evander.  Pallas is amazed (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 obstipuit}{\plain \fs24 \f1  -- \softline
verse 121) by Aeneas's cordial gesture and accedes to it.  The entire context there seems to fit the \softline
details of Dante's scene better, Dante as Aeneas 'invading' the homeland of those with whom he \softline
will be allied.  As Hollander has pointed out ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: The New Song and the Old," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura \softline
Dantis [virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 [1990], p. 37), the ominous undertones present in Virgil's scene (Aeneas will \softline
in fact bring not peace but war, one in which Pallas will become the central sacrificial partner) \softline
seem necessarily excluded here.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 75.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This final detail, on the other hand, does inject a note of moral tension, since it reveals \softline
the predisposition of these souls to linger where they are rather than to proceed upward.  See the \softline
note to vv. 10-12.  Their openness to negligence begins the conflict narrated in this second section \softline
of the canto, in which Casella's song will so engage them that they will finally have to be chastised \softline
by Cato.  See Francesco da Buti's comment to this verse, insisting on 'their negligence, which \softline
follows from their delight in wordly things.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The verse carries an overtone of a line in the passage from }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  describing the effect of \softline
Mars as music, moving the hearers to such a state that they 'quasi cessano da ogni operazione' \softline
(almost completely cease their activity).  See the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II.13-18.  Dante is, in effect, \softline
their 'music,' and they respond more to the miracle of his fleshly presence than to the sign of God's \softline
love that it gives, and which should be acknowledged.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 76-78.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This as yet unidentified soul (we will learn his name, Casella, at verse 91) has \softline
recognized Dante and advances to embrace him; Dante, filled with a proper Christian affection, \softline
responds to his embracer's emotion without any personalization, returning love for love without \softline
earthly distinctions.  It is a very good beginning for a pilgrim in purgatory.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 79-81.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This much-admired scene is modeled on another, but which one?  Virgil's epic \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.792-794 and VI.700-702) contains three identical lines of verse describing a failed \softline
embrace.  The first commentators opt for the latter, Aeneas's attempt to hold fast Anchises' \softline
paternal ghost.  But John of Serravalle, in his commentary to these lines, thinks, in a departure \softline
from that opinion, of Aeneas's identical effort to embrace the dead form of his wife, Creusa, in the \softline
second book.  He was followed by Vellutello (comm. to vv. 79-87).  Modern commentators \softline
almost universally return to the more familiar scene in Book VI, and it has been rare in the last \softline
century of glossing to find anyone even contemplating the earlier scene involving Creusa.  One \softline
would expect, perhaps, that commentators would at least discuss their options.  But such is not the \softline
case.  For reasons to prefer the less favored text, see Hollander ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: The New Song \softline
and the Old," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis [virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 [1990], p. 38 [but see his earlier identical view \softline
("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: Cato's Rebuke and Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 scoglio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Italica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  52 [1975], p. 349)]), pointing out that \softline
(1) the poet will later and unmistakably refer to Aeneas's attempted embrace of Anchises (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . 
XV.25-27) and arguing that it would be less than likely for him to do so here as well, since he had \softline
two such moments to choose from; (2) the context, in which Casella will shortly be singing a song \softline
of love to Dante, would argue for the greater appropriateness of Creusa to Anchises.  One \softline
discussant argues for a double reference here; see George Economou ("Self-Consciousness of \softline
Poetic Activity in Dante and Langland," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vernacular Poetics in the Middle Ages}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Lois Ebin \softline
[Kalamazoo: Medieval Institute Publications, 1984]), p. 180.  (For the supposed program of 'failed' \softline
embraces in this }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXI.130-136.)\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For the apostrophe of the 'empty shades, except in seeming' see, as Tommaseo suggested in \softline
1837, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VI.36, the phrase 'lor vanit{\f3 \'42} che par persona' (their emptiness, which seems real \softline
bodies).  The shades of the gluttons there and of all posthumous souls have this in common, but we \softline
must wait for Statius's long disquisition in canto XXV to learn how the 'aerial body' of the dead is \softline
produced.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 83.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Casella's smile is the first one we have seen since Limbo, when Virgil smiled to see the \softline
poets of antiquity welcome Dante as they prepared to include him in their noble company (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
IV.99).  Smiles, understandably absent from the visages of those in hell, will be more frequent in \softline
purgatory, some dozen of them, and still more so in paradise (two dozen).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 85-87.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Only after Dante hears Casella's voice does he recognize him, so distant seems the \softline
world of earth.  See the entirely similar moment with Forese Donati (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIII.43-45) and one \softline
somewhat similar with his sister Piccarda (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.58-63).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Both Dante and Casella are eager to stay and converse; we will soon enough understand \softline
that, for all the humanity and pleasantness of their attitudes, Cato has other plans for them.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 91.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Casella, finally named, was obviously, from the context of the scene, a musician.  That \softline
is really all we know with any certainty about him.  Nonetheless, it is clear that he is someone \softline
whom Dante actually knew.  Whether he was from Florence or Pistoia (or even Siena -- the \softline
commentators are puzzled and offer these possibilities, most of them plumping for Florence) we do \softline
not know.  Whether he actually set one or more of Dante's poems to music we do not know.  For \softline
some sense of his possible identity and activity see Luigi Peirone, 'Casella' (ED.1970.1); Fabio \softline
Bisogni ("Precisazioni sul Casella dantesco," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Quadrivium}{\plain \fs24 \f1  12 [1971(1974)], pp. 81-91) and \softline
Mahmoud Salem Elsheikh ("I musicisti di Dante [Casella, Lippo, Schochetto] in Nicol{\f3 \'62} de' Rossi," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  48 [1971], esp. pp. 156-58).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab It comes as something of a surprise to realize that Dante has not spoken since }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
XXXIV.100-105.  His silence in the first canto of the new }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is probably meant to suggest the \softline
awe he feels in this new, mysterious, and sacred place.  Casella, representing the familiarity of \softline
Tuscany, allows him to break the spell.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 93.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Casella has evidently been dead some time (for at least slightly more than three \softline
months, as verse 98 will make plain) and Dante wonders why he has been so long between death \softline
and his first step toward salvation, arrival in purgatory.  Beginning with Poletto (comm. to vv.  94-99) and Moore (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , First Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Scripture and Classical Authors in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Oxford: \softline
Clarendon, 1969 (1896)], p. 168, commentators have seen a connection here with Charon's \softline
unwillingness to take certain of the waiting shades across Acheron (they all are eager to be taken) \softline
and in fact picking and choosing among the waiting throng (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.315-316).  We might continue 
the thought: In Dante's poem Charon takes all bound for hell at once; only those bound for \softline
purgatory need to be winnowed by the transporting angel, with some having to stay longer in the \softline
world, near Ostia, thus mirroring a sort of prepurgation that the poet has invented, offstage, as it \softline
were. \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 94-105.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Casella's startling narrative at times escapes the sort of attention it requires.  This \softline
is what we learn: Before the Jubilee Year's plenary indulgence announced by Pope Boniface in \softline
February 1300 (retroactive to Christmas of 1299), all those who came to the region around Ostia, \softline
where the souls of the saved are gathered, had to await the pleasure of the angel to be taken \softline
aboard the ship that we have just seen Casella and the others disembark from.  Before 25 \softline
December 1299, Casella was denied many times a seat in the ship.  We are forced to understand \softline
that he was not gifted with a particularly energetic desire for God; i.e., he was a perfect 'brother' to \softline
the Dante we meet at the beginning of this canto, a man like those 'who think about the way and in \softline
their hearts go on -- while still their bodies linger' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.11-12).  Purgatory is thus divided into \softline
three spaces: the mountain of purgation itself, ante-purgatory, and 'pre-ante-purgatory,' located \softline
somewhere never described but at or near Ostia.  And the laws of this place themselves underwent \softline
a change in late 1299, for after that date }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 anyone}{\plain \fs24 \f1  who wanted to depart for the 'holy land' would be \softline
accommodated by the angel.  (Dante has apparently, on no authority but his own, decided that the \softline
plenary indulgence for sinners extended to the souls of the justified dead as well.)  This requires \softline
that we understand that during the past three months Casella }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 did not want}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to travel south toward \softline
heaven.  Given his behavior once he arrives at the shore, however, this is not totally surprising.  \softline
Finally, precisely three months after the merciful decree was made, he decided that he wanted to \softline
leave.  The date: 25 March 1300, the Florentine New Year.  Is it coincidence that this, the most \softline
likely date for the beginning of Dante's journey (see the notes to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.1; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.11; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.19-21), \softline
is also that on which Casella probably set out?  Whether or not it is, we have the delightful \softline
spectacle of these two miraculous voyagers, each starting somewhere in Italy, one gliding over the \softline
seas, the other moving under the earth, arriving at the antipodes within minutes of one another, \softline
reunited in friendship and peace.  (Poletto's discussion [comm. to vv. 94-99] of some of these \softline
problems is one of the few in which these complex matters are closely and suggestively examined.)\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 106-108.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The protagonist's language is laced with diametrically opposed terms: 'new law' \softline
and 'songs of love.'  Merely hearing them, one intuits that there is an oppositional relationship \softline
between them.  Daniello's commentary (1568) asserts that there is indeed a 'new law' in purgatory, \softline
where 'one does not sing vain and lascivious things, but hymns and psalms in praise of God, and \softline
prays to Him.'  In this first confrontation, looking ahead to the song not yet sung, the 113th Psalm \softline
is that of the 'New Law,' and is juxtaposed against the love song that Dante wrote for a woman in \softline
the last century.  It is this kind that, earthbound as he now again is, the protagonist longs for.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Petrocchi's text for verse 108 reads 'doglie' (sorrows) and not 'voglie' (longings).  Hardly \softline
any Dantist currently admires this choice, and the vast majority urges a return to the 1921 reading, \softline
including the translators.  For one of the stronger arguments for such a return see Gorni \softline
({\u8220\'93}Costanza della memoria e censura dell{\u8217\'92}umano nell{\u8217\'92}Antipurgatorio,{\u8221\'94} }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1\lang1040 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1\lang1040  54 (1982]), \softline
pp. 67-70; see also Frasca ("Dante, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II, 13, 44, 109.  Note filologiche ed esegetiche," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Esperienze letterarie}{\plain \fs24 \f1  9, 2 [1984]), pp. 83-88.  And see the similar locution (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.41): 'lor disio \softline
quetato,' where the verb }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 quetare}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is joined to a word for desire or longing.  Once again, we have \softline
followed Petrocchi, despite our disagreement.  But see Sanguineti's edition (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dantis Alagherii 
Comedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Edizioni del Galluzzo, 2001]) which prints }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 voglie}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 111.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's soul, wearied by his bodily weight, remembers his condition at the beginning \softline
of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.22: in simile, his mind, in stress, is like the breath of a man escaping from death by \softline
drowning, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 affannata}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (laboring).  If he seems better off now than he was then, he is still in \softline
considerable difficulty.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 112.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Casella's song is Dante's song, the second }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 canzone}{\plain \fs24 \f1  found in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  It was \softline
composed in celebration of Lady Philosophy.  That sounds innocent or even positive.  On the other \softline
hand, she is, early on in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , specifically designated as having replaced Beatrice in Dante's \softline
affections.  Within the confines of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  this is not problematic.  In the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , in which \softline
Beatrice is the moving force for so much, it is.  And thus some critics have embraced what seems \softline
at first an unlikely position: that Dante is here denigrating his affection for that lady.  For this \softline
argument see Ann Hallock ("Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 selva oscura}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and Other Obscure }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 selva}{\plain \fs24 \f1 s," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Forum Italicum}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 \softline
[1972]), pp. 72-74, and Hollander ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: Cato's Rebuke and Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 scoglio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Italica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  52 \softline
[1975]), pp. 353-55.  For a restatement of the more traditional view see Ignazio Baldelli \softline
("Linguistica e interpretazione: l'amore di Catone, di Casella, di Carlo Martello e le canzoni del \softline
{\u171\'ab}Convivio{\u187\'bb} II e III," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Miscellanea di studi linguistici in onore di Walter Belardi}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. P. \softline
Cipriano, P. Di Giovine, M. Mancini, vol. II [Rome: n. p., 1996], esp. p. 549).  As long ago as \softline
1955 Fausto Montanari ("Il canto secondo del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Humanitas}{\plain \fs24 \f1  10 [1955], pp. 359-63) \softline
interpreted the scene as being essentially oppositional, a position that was redeveloped in the 1970s \softline
by Freccero (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante: The Poetics of Conversion}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Rachel Jacoff [Cambridge: Harvard University \softline
Press, 1986], pp. 186-94) and Hollander ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: Cato's Rebuke and Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 scoglio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Italica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  52 [1975], pp. 348-63) and followed by several others, including Gorni ({\u8220\'93}Costanza della \softline
memoria e censura dell{\u8217\'92}umano nell{\u8217\'92}Antipurgatorio,{\u8221\'94} }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1\lang1040 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1\lang1040  54 [1982], pp. 58-62; \softline
Barolini (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's Poets}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1984]), pp. 31-40; and Edoardo \softline
Sanguineti ("Infernal Acoustics: Sacred Song and Earthly Song," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis [virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 \softline
[1990]), pp. 74-77.  For medieval musical theory as supporting this conception of an oppositional \softline
strategy in the structuring of the canto's two songs Amilcare see Iannucci ("Casella's Song and the \softline
Tuning of the Soul," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Thought}{\plain \fs24 \f1  65 [1990]), pp. 42-44.  But for general opposition to such ways of \softline
reading the episode see Baldelli ("Linguistica e interpretazione: l'amore di Catone, di Casella, di \softline
Carlo Martello e le canzoni del {\u171\'ab}Convivio{\u187\'bb} II e III," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Miscellanea di studi linguistici in onore di \softline
Walter Belardi}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. P. Cipriano, P. Di Giovine, M. Mancini, vol. II [Rome: n. p., 1996], pp. 535-55), and Muresu ("L'inno e il canto d'amore,"}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  La Rassegna della letteratura italiana}{\plain \fs24 \f1  104 [2000], \softline
pp. 5-48).  For a rejoinder to Hollander see Pertile ("Dante, lo scoglio e la vesta," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Da una riva e \softline
